    "id": 349,
    "title": "History of Panjim",
    "poi_id": 0,
    "description": "Our walking tour starts just outside the Panjim bus stand. <p>Welcome to the city of Panajim. Panjim or \"the land that never floods\" was originally a small fishing village abounding in coconut groves, creeks and fields. Originally a ward of Taleigao village it so enamored Adil Shah that he built his summer palace on the bank of the Mandovi river, which later became the Government Secretariat.</p> <p>Panjim or 'New Goa' gained importance in the 1820s, after it replaced Old Goa as the administrative seat for the Portuguese government. It's architectural styles, with its Latin influences, like the overhanging verandahs, courtyards, sheltered porches, balconies and high roofs make it a unique city. Structures are often painted in indigo, ochre and terracotta and white is usually reserved for churches and chapels.</p> <p>Panjim is flanked by the river Mandovi on the North, and the hillock of Altinho on the south. It includes old quarters like Fontainhas as well as the modern Patto Plaza it's corporate district. It is one of the best-planned cities in the country thanks to the noted engineer Luis A de Maravilhas, among others. A neat grid of broad avenues and connecting roads, footpaths with provisions for tree planting, a good sewage system, gardens and sedate architecture with Latin influences, earn it the sobriquet of 'Princess of the Mandovi'</p> <p>More than 170 years old, Panjim has evolved from a sandy, swampy coconut grove into an individualistic modern city yet, retaining its quaint old-world charm.</p>",
