    "id": 310,
    "title": "Casa da Moeda",
    "poi_id": 3,
    "description": "<p> Casa Da Moeda literally means <b>House of Coins</b> in Portuguese. The Viceroy of Goa, unhappy with the quality of coins minted in Old Goa ordered the mint to be shifted to New Goa. It stands in the Post Office Square, between the Post Office and the Mandovi river. Coins were minted here for seven years between 1834-1841 after which it was moved to the arsenal in Panjim. In 1870, coins were requisitioned from the Bombay Mint and in 1878, all existing coinage became obsolete.</p> <p>In 1963, Casa Da Moeda was sold to Antonia Inacio Da Silva. It was then rented to the British Telegraph briefly before it was sold to the Dias family in 1904, which are the present owners. It was one of the few buildings in India that was occupied by both the British and Portuguese.</p><p>The tiled roof, attic windows, wooden verandah and yellow arches evoke a bygone era. The building is raised off the ground and supported by masonry arches, which were built in the 1800s. It's high ceiling, Dutch doors, wooden floors and fragile window panes make it a marvel of architecture and antiquity.</p><p>A festival of art and literature is organized regularly by the Dias family, to commemorate more than 175 years of Casa Da Moeda.</p>",
