    "poi_id": 5,
    "description": "<p>The Head Post office is a brightly colored red and white bungalow, which dominates the Tobacco square, over-looking the Mandovi river. It is located in the Sao Tome ward that lies north to Fontainhas.</p><p>It was originally a depot for trading tobacco. The Portuguese brought tobacco to the Indian subcontinent 200 years before the British. It was used as a police headquarters briefly before it was turned into the Head Post Office in 1854. Mail was routed through Bombay with British India stamps, which were available in Goa. In 1871, the Portuguese issued the first Portugal stamps for use within the colony and continued issuing stamps till 1960. From 1877, the words 'India Post' or 'Servico Postal' was included on its service.</p>",
