    "id": 319,
    "title": "Sao Tome Chapel",
    "poi_id": 6,
    "description": "<p>In the corner of the Tobacco Square in Fontainhas, is an elegant white chapel dedicated to St. Thomas. In Goa, St. Thomas is the patron saint of architects and builders. and the area was initially full of artisans.</p><p>More than 400 years old, the original chapel was built in 1814, just a little distance from the present one. The new chapel, in its current location took four years to build and was blessed on July 8th, 1849. There have been several renovations over the years. It was re-opened in 1961, in the last year of Portuguese rule in Goa.</p><p>In front of the chapel was the town pillory, which was a device similar to the 'stocks' for punishment and public humiliation of the erring. It was made of a wooden or metal framework erected on a post, with holes for securing the head and hands. The offender had to bend forward and stick his head and hands forward in a most uncomfortable manner. Sometimes a placard detailing the nature of the crime was placed next to it. People would gather around it to taunt, tease and laugh at the offender. </p>",
