    "id": 328,
    "title": "Chapel of St. Sebastian",
    "poi_id": 8,
    "description": "In 1818, a small chapel was built to cater to the spiritual needs of the residents of the new settlement of Fontainhas. It is an important landmark that dominates the Fontainhas area. The right wing of the chapel houses a striking life-size crucifix, which once hung in the Palace of the Inquisition in Old Goa and was used in the processions, preceding the sitting of the Tribunal of the Inquisition. This statue is considered unusual as the image of Christ has its eyes wide open and was believed to be created, to instill fear in the minds of those being interrogated by the Inquisitors. It contains historic images and relics from other churches and convents around Goa, which, due to suppression of the religious orders from the Portuguese government, were demolished or shut down. The intricate woodwork on the alters are a study in craftsmanship. ",
