    "id": 347,
    "title": "Fonte Phoenix",
    "poi_id": 13,
    "description": "<p>'Fonte Phoenix' is an ancient, natural spring of crystalline water at the foot of Marutigad of the Altinho hillock. Till mid-18th century this area was alluvial soil with a few paddy fileds. A wealthy gentleman Antonio Joao de sequira nicknamed 'Mossmikar' as he had returned from the Portuguese colony of Mozambique bought the land and leveled it for a coconut grove. It was called 'Palmeira Ponte' literally meaning 'bridge coconut grove'.</p><p>An artistic structure of basalt stone was constructed around the natural spring in the 1850s, during the tenure of the Portuguese Governor, Viscount of Ourem, Joaquim Jose Januario Lapa.</p><p>It provided three taps of potable drinking water to the new settlement of Fontainhas and the rest of the city of Panjim.</p><p>The Hindu residential area of the precinct has families like the Agshikars, Hodarkars, Pissurlenkars, Shirodkars, Shankwalkars, etc. who have lived there since the Portuguese times. So also Christian families like the Mirandas, Lopes, Saldanhas, Costas, Gonsalves, Dias, Rego, Menezes, Machados, Ribeiros and others have made Fontainhas their home.</p>",
